commitResults.messageBody:
Constructors for Deadline and Event are too cluttered.

Extracting lines of code out into methods results in better code clarity and better
readability.

Extracting the lines for parsing date in string format into LocalDate format into a
private method makes the constructor look much cleaner and less cluttered.

Putting the date parsing into a method makes the code more readable and cleaner.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix minor coding standard infractions
Add assertions for Deadline and Event class methods
commitResults.messageBody:
Current methods have no assertions to ensure proper flow of
execution.

Adding assertions ensure that no variables are null when passed
into the method to ensure no unexpected outputs.

Let's add assertions to check for null variables.

This checks for erroneous function inputs and ensures that the
code is executed the way it is intended to.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix minor coding standard infractions
Shift parseDate method in Deadline and Event class to Task parent class
commitResults.messageBody:
Both Deadline and Event class have the same method for parsing a date in
string format.

This breaks the DRY principle as there is a duplication of methods in the
code base.

Let's shift the method to their parent class Task so the method is inherited
instead.

Inheriting the method ensures that there is no duplication of code and the
DRY principle is adhered to.
